y Southern men living in or close to rural landscapes, hunting is a passion. But it is not a timeless activity in a cultural void. Whether pursuers of fox or raccoon, deer or rabbits, quail or dove, Southern hunters reveal for Stuart Marks complex patterns of male bonding, social status, and relationships with nature. Marks, who has written two outstanding books on hunting in Africa, was born and has long lived in the South. Examining Southern hunting from frontier times through the antebellum era to the present day, he shows it to be a litmus test of rural identity. "Drawing on the latest anthropological theory, statistical sources, extensive interviews, and historical research, [Marks] has crafted a multifaceted account of Southern hunting. Relations of race, property, gender, and region appear in fresh guises in this innovative and intriguing study. The portrayal of the contemporary state of hunting is especially interesting, revealing both the continuities with the past and the new pressures on the sport."--Virginia Quarterly Review  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aHuntingxSocial aspectszNorth Carolina. 0aHuntingzNorth Carolina. 0aSocial classeszNorth Carolina. 0aSocial statuszNorth Carolina. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAudubon Society.  aBeausejour (plantation).  aCamellia Acres.  aCape Fear River.  aCarolina hinterlands.  aChampion.  aDual Champion, foxhounds.  aElliott, William.  aGrand Champion.  aHighlanders.  aJordan Creek.  aLake Mattamuskeet.  aMexican quail.  aNational Wildlife Federation.  aOld Laurel Hill.  aPee Dee River.  aagribusinessmen.  aagriculture.  ababbling (in dogs).  abag limit.  abird shot.  ablacks.  abuck hunting.  aconservation.  acoon club.  acoon hunting.  adecoys.  adeer head, symbolism.  adoc